<DOC><DOCNO> AP881007-0097 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1115EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Explosion 1stLd-Writethru a0553 10-07 0284</FIRST><SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Explosion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,0291</SECOND><HEAD>Bookstore Explosion Injures Two; Bomb Found In A Second Store</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with bombing Thursday. No pickup.</NOTE><DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An explosion today damaged abookstore in a white suburb of Durban and injured two people,police said. Shortly afterward, a bomb was found in a downtownbranch of the store.   The blast occurred around 2 p.m. at the Central News Agencybookstore in suburban Pinetown, police said.   About an hour later, police said they found a bomb at a CentralNews Agency branch in downtown Durban. Police evacuated thousandsof people from surrounding office buildings and cordoned off thearea, witnesses said.   On Thursday, six people were hurt, including one seriously, whena bomb exploded outside the municipal offices of a mixed-racetownship near Johannesburg, police said.   A limpet mine placed in a trash bin also damaged windows andwalls of the municipal building in Tembisa, east of Johannesburg,police added.   The victims included three men and three women, police said. Thegovernment-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said one of thewomen was in serious condition.   There have been almost daily bombings in recent weeks in SouthAfrica. The 29 bombings in September were the most ever in thecountry in a single month.   Police have blamed virtually all of the attacks on the outlawedAfrican National Congress, the main black guerrilla groupattempting to overthrow the white-led government.   Police say the ANC has intensified its bombing campaign in a bidto disrupt the nationwide municipal elections set for Oct. 26.   There have been about 150 bombings in South Africa since thegovernment declared a nationwide state of emergency in June 1986.</TEXT></DOC>